data.content:
Your test works but `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "Expected: True, Actual: False"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with clear diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);                          // instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));         // no built-in "all match" assert — IsTrue is fine here
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);                         // instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users); // or just:
    // Assert.IsNotNull(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key collection assertions available:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(list)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, list)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Contains(x))` | `Assert.Contains(x, list)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` |
| `list.Single()` + null check | `Assert.ContainsSingle(list)` |

The benefit: on failure you get messages like `"Expected count: 3, Actual: 2"` instead of just `"Assert.IsTrue failed"`.
